This executive order, issued on January 8, 2021, establishes the order of succession for the Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) in the event that the Administrator and the Deputy Administrator are unable to perform their duties. The order lists the officials who will act as Administrator in the specified order. The order also specifies exceptions, stating that acting officials listed in the order cannot serve as Administrator and that the President has the discretion to depart from the order in designating an acting Administrator. Additionally, this order revokes Executive Order 13763 issued on January 13, 2017, which provided a previous order of succession within the EPA. The order concludes by stating that it does not create any enforceable rights or benefits against the United States or any other party. The order is signed by Donald J. Trump, the President, and is effective immediately.